'''Joshua David Steven King''' (born 3 January 2007) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[central midfielder]] for [[Premier League]] club [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] and the [[England national football team|England national team]].<ref name="scholar">{{cite news |url=https://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2024/june/07/king-wins-scholar-of-the-year/|title=King Wins Scholar of the Year|first=Laurie|last=Martin|website=Fulham F.C.|date=7 June 2024|access-date=6 December 2024}}</ref>

==Early life==
King was educated at [[Hampton School]] in South West London where he also played an integral role in the school's ESFA Cup win in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Sports RoundUp|url=https://hamptonschool.org.uk/2024/12/sports-roundup-6/|website=Hampton School|date=2024-12-12|access-date=2026-01-30|language=en-GB|first=Sarah|last=Dearden}}</ref>

==Club career==
King joined the [[Fulham F.C. Under-21s and Academy|Fulham academy]] aged eight and in June 2024<ref>{{Cite web|title=King Wins Scholar of the Year|url=https://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2024/june/07/king-wins-scholar-of-the-year/|website=Fulham FC|date=2024-06-07|access-date=2026-01-30|first=Fulham|last=FC}}</ref> he won scholar of the year after being rewarded with his first professional contract with Fulham in the January of the first year.<ref name="scholar"/>

On 27 August 2024, King made his professional club debut for [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] coming on as a second-half substitute in an [[EFL Cup]] game against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2024/august/27/birmingham-city-0-2-fulham/|title=Birmingham City 0–2 Fulham|first=Daniel|last=O'Sullivan|website=Fulham F.C.|date=27 August 2024|accessdate=29 December 2024}}</ref> On 5 December 2024, he made his first [[Premier League]] appearance in a victory over [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2024/december/05/josh-one-of-the-best-moments-of-my-life/|title=Josh: One of the best moments of my life|website=Fulham F.C.|date=5 December 2024|access-date=29 December 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c99x0100k7dt|title=Fulham 3–1 Brighton & Hove Albion|first=Michael|last=Emons|work=BBC Sport|date=5 December 2024|accessdate=29 December 2024}}</ref> On 22 December 2024 King made his first start in the Premier League against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2024/december/23/man-of-the-match-result--southampton/|title=Man of the Match result: Southampton|first=Daniel|last=O'Sullivan|website=Fulham F.C.|date=23 December 2024|accessdate=11 August 2025}}</ref>

On 17 July 2025 Fulham confirmed King had signed a new four year deal with the club, a contract which will run until 30 June 2029.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2025/july/17/long-term-deal-for-king/|title=Long-Term deal for King|first=Geoff|last=Pruce|website=Fulham F.C.|date=17 July 2025|accessdate=11 August 2025}}</ref>

On 28 October 2025 King scored his first goal for Fulham against [[Wycombe Wanderers F.C.|Wycombe Wanderers]] in the EFL Cup fourth round.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Brotherton |first=Alex |date=28 October 2025 |title=Fulham beat Wycombe on penalties to reach EFL Cup last eight |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/czxk41dkll9t |access-date=29 October 2025 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

King scored his first  Premier League goal on 21 March 2026, in a 3–1 victory over [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-03-21 |title=Saturday wrap: Race for Europe hots up as big guns stunned |url=https://www.premierleague.com/en/news/4619068/saturday-wrap-race-for-europe-hots-up-as-big-guns-stunned |access-date=2026-03-22 |website=www.premierleague.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Press |first=Associated |last2=Media |first2=P. A. |date=2026-03-21 |title=Raúl Jiménez honours late father after penalty seals Fulham win over Burnley |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2026/mar/21/fulham-burnley-premier-league-match-report |access-date=2026-03-22 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

==International career==
In August 2022 King captained [[England national under-16 football team|England under-16]] against [[Italy national under-16 football team|Italy]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/ng-interactive/2023/oct/10/next-generation-2023-20-of-the-best-talents-at-premier-league-clubs|title=Next Generation 2023: 20 of the best talents at Premier League clubs|first1=Marcus|last1=Christenson|first2=Steven|last2=Bloor|first3=Garry|last3=Blight|website=The Guardian|date=10 October 2023|accessdate=29 December 2024}}</ref> He was a member of the [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]] squad at the [[2025 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]] and scored a goal during a 5–5 group stage draw with [[Germany national youth football team|Germany]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c15nje19wy7t|title=England 5–5 Germany|first=Neil|last=Johnston|work=BBC Sport|date=17 June 2025|access-date=18 November 2025}}</ref>

King made his [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]] debut on 10 October 2025 during a 4–0 victory away to [[Moldova national under-21 football team|Moldova]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2025/Oct/11/england-mens-under-19s-v-belgium-match-report-20251110|title=Report: England MU19s 4–1 Belgium|first=Holly|last=Hunt|website=EnglandFootball.com|date=10 October 2025|access-date=11 October 2025}}</ref> The following month saw him score his first goal at this level in an away win against [[Slovakia national under-21 football team|Slovakia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c93d4ep8edyt|title=Slovakia 0–4 England|first=Michael|last=Emons|work=BBC Sport|date=18 November 2025|access-date=18 November 2025}}</ref>

On 23 May 2026, it was announced King was one of four players (alongside [[Ethan Nwaneri]], [[Alex Scott (footballer, born 2003)|Alex Scott]] and [[Rio Ngumoha]]) that would join the [[England national football team|senior team]] for the squad's preparation camp before the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Young England talents to join Three Lions in Florida |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2026/May/22/young-england-talents-to-join-three-lions-in-florida |website=englandfootball.com |publisher=[[The Football Association]] |date=23 May 2026}}</ref>

